It is important to recognize that with this solution approach, the understanding of the limiting rates is being used to infer regulatory interactions from the âtop down,â i.e., starting from the observed functioning of the overall system and then decomposing this into sub-components. This is an unconventional strategy for modeling regulatory interactions like cyclic electron flow, non-photochemical quenching, and photosynthetic control. It may at first seem counterintuitive because it does not explicitly resolve the acidification of the thylakoid lumen, alkalinization of the stroma, and development of an electric field across the thylakoid membrane (e.g., Oja etÂ al. 2011; Tikhonov 2013). These phenomena are often modeled with a âbottom-upâ approach that aims to piece together the detailed mechanisms that mediate the generation of the proton motive force, its partitioning into ÎÏ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
