				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {b}_{6}\hbox {f}$$\end{document}, and the decrease in efficiency is caused by the simultaneous accumulation of closed reaction centers. In these simulations, the PAR absorptance has been varied while maintaining a constant partitioning of absorbed light between PS I and PS II. The resulting variation in the amount of light reaching PS I and PS II alters the initial slope and apparent curvature of the light response, i.e., the half-saturation point of Eq.Â 30a (Fig.Â 6a). The variation in the potential rates of LEF and CEF1 does not influence the partitioning between LEF and CEF1 (Fig.Â 6b), but does drive variation in the potential rates of gross CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
