Next, we examine a simulation in which photosynthetic control is achieved purely via feedback on NPQ (Fig.Â 7, Case 6). In this simulation, feedback acts on NPQ alone to balance the rates of LEF and CEF1 to the activities of the PCR and PCO cycles (Fig.Â 7e). There is no NPQ under limiting light and a strong acceleration in the rate of increase in NPQ above the light saturation point (Fig.Â 7f). The absence of NPQ under limiting light intensities reflects the fact that the absorption cross-sections are balanced and there is no connectivity prescribed for the PS II antennae. As a result, the closure of PS I and PS II remains balanced under limiting light (Fig.Â 7g). At and above the light saturation point, the increase in NPQ poises the plastoquinone pool at a point where the rate of electron flow through PS II remains in balance with the excitation of PS I without any further feedback on Cyt b6f\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
