				\begin{document}$$\hbox {b}_{6}\hbox {f}$$\end{document}-limited and Rubisco-limited states.

The potential role(s) of CEF1 in photosynthetic control have been much discussed in relation to the phenotypes of the pgrl1 and pgr5 mutants, and this model offers a new quantitative lens on this problem (e.g., Munekage etÂ al. 2001, 2002, and subsequent studies). Since the gas-exchange and fluorescence measurements we made in this study do not provide direct constraints on CEF1, we formulated this model to represent the lower and upper bounds on CEF1: the minimum potential CEF1 that would be required by the ATP demands of carbon metabolism, and the maximum potential CEF1 that could be driven by the PS I excitation in excess of the demands of carbon metabolism (Fig.Â 1; cyclic electron flow). These bounds lead to three questions about how regulation negotiates the transition from limiting to saturating light. First, is the downregulation of Cyt b6f\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
